		<tr>
		  <td valign="top" width="60" align="center" class="borderClass" style="border: 0;"><div class="picSurround"><a href="/profile/Kuiper"><img src="http://cdn.myanimelist.net/images/userimages/thumbs/331692_thumb.jpg" vspace="4" border="0"></a></div></td>
		  <td class="borderClass" style="border: 0;" valign="top">
		  <div style="margin-bottom: 6px;"><a href="/profile/Kuiper">Kuiper</a> <small><span style="font-weight: normal;"> | 04-24-14, 5:32 PM</span></small></div>
		  Guys and gals, allow me to tell you a short story, from several summers ago, recalling events from my adolescent years.<br />
<br />
Guys and gals, allow me to tell you a short story, from several summers ago.<br />
<br />
I used to live in a pretty rural area, and my family lived near the edge of town. The only other person my age that was within walking distance of our house when I grew up was a girl named Emily who lived at the other end of a vacant lot on the corner at the end of my street. Being the same age, we had been in the same classes through elementary school and become good friends at that age, often going over to each other's houses to play.<br />
<br />
However, during middle school, we sort of split paths. I was on the "accelerated learning track" and she was taking regular classes, so we never had class together. We grew apart during those high school years, only occasionally seeing each other in the hallways; we gravitated to different social circles so I'd never eat with her during lunch or go to the same after school activities as her. The one time I remember talking to her in middle school was near the end of eighth grade, and I learned that we would be going to different high schools. It seemed as though our childhood friendship would be entirely terminated at that point. Until the end of the school year when we had our last summer before high school.<br />
<br />
<br />
The first day of summer vacation was a Friday, so I followed morning routine like any other week day since there weren't Saturday-morning cartoons on to disrupt my schedule. I got up at 6, poured myself a bowl of cereal, retrieved the paper from the front door step and read the comics whilst ingesting breakfast. Usually after doing this I would walk directly to school, but after I exited the house that morning, I decided to walk the other way. That direction took me toward the vacant lot by Emily's house. It was there that I saw her sitting on a large rock, staring off into space.<br />
<br />
I walked up to her and said "hey," and she nodded without looking at me. Acting on an impulse, I sat down next to her, and immediately regretted doing so. We shared an awkward silence and sat there for several minutes before she mumbled something about her mom and went back into her house.<br />
<br />
The next morning, I skipped cartoons and went straight to her door before I became too afraid to knock and went back to the lot where I sat on the same rock. After awhile I got bored, so I went back to my house, got a book, and went back to the rock. I was on the rock for what was probably an hour before she walked out, looked at me, and sat down next to me.<br />
<br />
I don't exactly recall our dialog, but it was something like this:<br />
<br />
Her: What are you reading?<br />
Me: The Foundation.<br />
Her: What's it about?<br />
Me: It's the chronicle of a group of mathematical savants who isolate themselves in a corner of the galaxy, thriving on their ability to predict events based entirely on calculation.<br />
Her: Oh.<br />
<br />
I regretted my calculated attempt at grandiloquence, and we again shared an awkward silence for several minutes before I got up and walked back to my house.<br />
<br />
The next morning, I walked out to the lot and she was waiting on the sidewalk, and we sort of shuffled our way toward the rock at the same pace before sitting down and staring off into the distance. We never looked directly at each other and didn't speak a word to each other.<br />
<br />
It became a daily ritual. We'd rise with the sun, head to the vacant lot, and engage in some mindless activity. Sometimes it was just sitting and doing nothing, sometimes we'd meander to the outskirts of town (we were already pretty close) and then walk back. Sometimes we'd climb a tree, or walk along the railroad tracks that ran behind my house, trying to balance ourselves on the rails.<br />
<br />
There were some days when one of us wouldn't show up, and the next day we'd exchange a few words, usually a short "I had to go do some stuff with my family yesterday," and that would be the end of it. We never really talked beyond exchanging a "hey" or "what's up" as a greeting.<br />
<br />
Our relationship was not a romance. We were both fully aware that we were not peers on intellectual or social levels, and having just reached the age where we might begin dating, I'm sure we both knew that the prospect of dating each other was entirely outside the realm of possibility. I think that's why we were silent. Middle school had drawn us apart because of how different we discovered we were, and I think we wanted to emulate our early years, when we were playmates and were too busy having fun to realize or consider our differences.<br />
<br />
One morning, she came out to the vacant lot, and we began walking. "My family's going on vacation tomorrow," she said. I asked her how long she'd be gone. "Not until after school starts." With that, we were both fully aware that this would in all likelihood be the last day we'd spend together, and I awkwardly suggested that we go to my house to make some sandwiches, the implication being that we'd be together the entire day and not go into town to eat. She agreed, and after having packed ourselves enough to cover our dietary needs for the day, we set out. We methodically covered all of our old Stomping Ground, and after that just followed the train tracks away from our block to see where they'd take us. Along the way, we chanced upon a tree which we climbed without speaking to one another, and we spent the rest of the day in that tree, watching the train tracks and counting the cars when trains went by. More than once that day, I wondered what it might be like to jump onto one of those trains with Emily and never return home. In the hours we spent there, there was so much that I wanted to tell her. I wanted to tell her what a wonderful companion she had been, that I was sorry that we'd fallen apart during middle school, how I wanted to be able to continue seeing each other in high school, and yet acknowledge that we were very different people with very different interests. I never said any of that, however, and the day drew to a close without us exchanging any of the sentiments that I'm sure we both longed to express.<br />
<br />
On the way home, those thoughts tugged at my heart, and I deliberately slowed pace to prolong our return. She immediately realized what was going on, and responded in kind; we took the most roundabout way we reasonably could have while following the way home. Anyway, we got too close to the train tracks and my friend Emily was killed. I hope your summer turns out well!<br />
</td>
		</tr>
