		<br><div id="comment11846397" class="bgNone"><table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
		<tr>
		  <td valign="top" width="60" align="center" class="borderClass" style="border: 0;"><div class="picSurround"><a href="/profile/Stellio"><img src="http://cdn.myanimelist.net/images/userimages/thumbs/1158933_thumb.jpg" vspace="4" border="0"></a></div></td>
		  <td class="borderClass" style="border: 0;" valign="top">
		  <div style="margin-bottom: 6px;"><a href="/profile/Stellio">Stellio</a> <small><span style="font-weight: normal;"> | 04-20-14, 4:32 PM</span></small></div>
		  @lpf: I'll contribute, let's do it bud! <br />
<br />
@RMNSkeptic: (This is super late so hopefully you haven't lost interest in it!)<br />
<br />
Having no ratings is fine. People have lists that are entirely private, so to say that ratings are entirely personalized and subjective is correct. With that said, I rate things for really two reasons: accessibility and continuity. People who access my list, as lpf and others have pointed out, are capable of having a quick cursory glimpse at my "taste" ("t" "a" "s" "t" "e" is a silly word but there's no better word for it, unfortunately). And for many, their purpose may be curiosity, scrutiny, whatever, but I organize my list for things such as future recommendation, as lpf had elaborated on previously. (And it's fairly self-explanatory that I'll recommend my 10s over 9s, 9s over 8s, and so on, but that may not always be the case)<br />
<br />
My feelings towards a work often change after some time, so my numbers are also fixated there to remind me of a passing thought. It's in the process of associating scores with certain assets of a show that I find value in condensing writing into numerical data. Others do something similar, probably, but yes, these can turn into unhealthy, schizophrenic penchants once applied meticulously or excessively.<br />
<br />
So in the end, I recommend rating largely for memory and personalized uses of ratings (why give a shit about what others think!). If one's visual memory is so vast or their writing skills are so competent as to be able to write about everything they watch (or they're rebels like, who cares about ratings), then by all means, eliminate the evil Ratings onslaught. <br />
<br />
On the flip side, MAL compatibility is pretty flawed and nigh arbitrary. Xinil should, but probably won't uh ever fix that.<br />
<br />
<div class="spoiler"><input type="button" class="button" onClick="this.nextSibling.nextSibling.style.display='block';this.style.display='none';" value="Show spoiler"> <span class="spoiler_content" style="display:none"><input type="button" class="button" onClick="this.parentNode.style.display='none';this.parentNode.parentNode.childNodes[0].style.display='block';" value="Hide spoiler"><br>"I've also noticed a sort of unhealthy way of watching anime fostered by people preoccupied with scores. People spend an episode reflecting on how minute things change the way they'll score it rather than allowing themselves to be swept up in it."<!--spoiler--></span></div><br />
This is where I can agree and rebel (rebels!) against the entire "Let's-Rate-Or-Review-Things-Before-They're-Finished" (excluding one episode OVAs, long running shows beyond a certain point, -- special cases etc.) Postulate/Dogma/Doctrine/Wrongness. More times than not, it's unfair to judge something that way. Yeah, first impressions count, but to utterly dismiss or indulge in a show-- that's something else. <br />
<br />
<div class="spoiler"><input type="button" class="button" onClick="this.nextSibling.nextSibling.style.display='block';this.style.display='none';" value="Show spoiler"> <span class="spoiler_content" style="display:none"><input type="button" class="button" onClick="this.parentNode.style.display='none';this.parentNode.parentNode.childNodes[0].style.display='block';" value="Hide spoiler"><br>"I also think scoring categories individually like on MAL reviews is idiotic. For story, animation, etc to always be given the same weight is to ignore how appropriate/important each is for their respective anime"<!--spoiler--></span></div><br />
The typical MAL review format is disastrous for this reason. That's not to say that's the case for all reviews in such a format (i.e. separated in Story, Animation, etc.), but when the writer dismisses the objective of all the elements working together to form isolated, convenient statements about the work, then it becomes a sort of lazy writing. MAL isn't the sole example of this, and definitely isn't the first. But it's definitely an insufferable breeding ground for it. An extreme "critic," though I won't do names, have even separated his reviews into entire sections of chunks such as "Proper Mindset," "Character Presence," "Catharsis," "Memorability," and "Legacy." And anyway, I think that just epitomizes everything that's wrong with dissecting works into chunks in a review. <br />
<br />
<div class="spoiler"><input type="button" class="button" onClick="this.nextSibling.nextSibling.style.display='block';this.style.display='none';" value="Show spoiler"> <span class="spoiler_content" style="display:none"><input type="button" class="button" onClick="this.parentNode.style.display='none';this.parentNode.parentNode.childNodes[0].style.display='block';" value="Hide spoiler"><br>"The idea of that seems anti-art to me"<!--spoiler--></span></div><br />
That's Dadaism. :)</td>
		</tr>
		</table>
