		<tr>
		  <td valign="top" width="60" align="center" class="borderClass" style="border: 0;"><div class="picSurround"><a href="/profile/Kuiper"><img src="http://cdn.myanimelist.net/images/userimages/thumbs/331692_thumb.jpg" vspace="4" border="0"></a></div></td>
		  <td class="borderClass" style="border: 0;" valign="top">
		  <div style="margin-bottom: 6px;"><a href="/profile/Kuiper">Kuiper</a> <small><span style="font-weight: normal;"> | 04-20-14, 11:55 AM</span></small></div>
		  I used to shy away from the idea of trying to "quantify" how much I like things with numerical scores, but I got more into scoring things after another ratings site I used implemented a rating system that included adjectives along with each rating.<br />
<br />
While assigning arbitrary numbers like "7," "8," etc doesn't jive exceptionally well with me, I personally already mentally sort things into categories like "mediocre," "almost good," "decent," "excellent," etc.  So after looking at my own list on MAL, I instead tried to segregate the ratings system from its numerical expression, and instead came up with a list of 10 adjectives, and I assign numerical ratings on MAL based on which adjective I think best describes my thoughts on the series.<br />
<br />
Granted, grouping things into categories like this is no less arbitrary than a numerical score; who's to say what is "decent" versus "mediocre?"   But as noted earlier, this kind of mental sorting is something that I do already, so I find it a bit cathartic to log onto MAL and "put it into writing," so to speak.</td>
		</tr>
		</table>
		</div>
