		  <td valign="top" width="60" align="center" class="borderClass" style="border: 0;"><div class="picSurround"><a href="/profile/jal90"><img src="http://cdn.myanimelist.net/images/userimages/thumbs/402245_thumb.jpg" vspace="4" border="0"></a></div></td>
		  <td class="borderClass" style="border: 0;" valign="top">
		  <div style="margin-bottom: 6px;"><a href="/profile/jal90">jal90</a> <small><span style="font-weight: normal;"> | 04-19-14, 12:21 AM</span></small></div>
		  The thing about this discussion is that, while I don't see a substantial reason to rate things, I don't see either a substantial reason to not rate them. As corwin said, to a point this is about being used to the dynamics, but I would mention as well that the fact scores and commentaries or reviews are so different is the reason why they can coexist.<br />
<br />
In the case of MyAnimeList, for instance this rating system is useful for a number of things. On the personal level because it's a brief and easy way to check what I have watched, how have my tastes evolved through the years, etc. On the social level because many features that depend on ratings and are potentially useful (namely compatibility, automated recommendations from sites like MALGraph), and as well because they provide an information and contextualize it since the rating can be compared with others. And finally, because I'm a sucker for stats.<br />
<br />
In the end, if people ask me to expand and/or explain my ratings I will do. This is not a big deal to me. And I use forums, comments and review systems to talk about stuff more in depth. This is not incompatible with having a list that gives a simplified and hierarchised glance at my overall taste.</td>
		</tr>
